<NewsletterIssueLayout num="006" title="The constraint is the feature" date="April 2026">

<div class="issue-section">
  <p class="issue-intro">I've been thinking about why the tools I return to are the ones that constrain me — iA Writer over Notion, a mechanical watch over a smart one, a walk over a gym session.</p>
</div>

<div class="issue-section">
  <figure>
    <div style="aspect-ratio: 16/9; background: #2a2a3a; border-radius: 2px; width: 100%;"></div>
    <figcaption>iA Writer on macOS. A cursor, a typeface, and nothing else.</figcaption>
  </figure>
</div>

<div class="issue-section">
  <span class="issue-section-label">On my mind</span>
  <h2 class="issue-section-title">Constraints as creative material</h2>
  <p class="issue-body-text">iA Writer does one thing: it lets you write. No databases, no page layout, no formatting toolbar. Just you, a cursor, and markdown.</p>
  <p class="issue-body-text">Oliver Reichenstein talks about radical simplification — going back to roots. When you strip away everything that isn't essential, you find out what the thing actually is.</p>
  <p class="issue-body-text">I've started applying this to my own work. When I design a workshop: what's the one thing? The constraint isn't the enemy. The constraint is the material.</p>
</div>

